{"time": "2016-09-05T12:32:26.312255", "block": {"tests_archive": null, "animation": null, "feedback_correct": "", "subtitles": {}, "source": null, "text": "<b></b><b><span class=\"wysiwyg-color-red\"><span class=\"wysiwyg-color-green\">Note:</span></span></b> If you have programming experience in python and know what a <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://docs.python.org/2/tutorial/datastructures.html#dictionaries\">dictionary</a> is, then congratulations, you have been using a <b><span class=\"wysiwyg-color-green\">Hash Map</span><i> </i></b><span class=\"wysiwyg-color-green\"><span class=\"wysiwyg-color-black\">all\n along and are already one step (no pun intended) ahead of us! If you \nhave no clue what we are talking about, then read on!<br></span></span><p></p><p><span class=\"wysiwyg-color-green\"><span class=\"wysiwyg-color-black\">By now we have seen the benefits of a <b><span class=\"wysiwyg-color-purple\">Hash Table</span></b> and are hopefully convinced that if we want to store data of <i>any</i> type and retrieve it fast, a <b><span class=\"wysiwyg-color-purple\">Hash Table</span></b> is the data structure to use. However, so far we've only been given the opportunity to store one object at a time (the <b><span class=\"wysiwyg-color-blue\">key</span></b>). For example, if we had a class of students, we could either store all their names or all their grades<span class=\"wysiwyg-color-green\"><span class=\"wysiwyg-color-black\">, but not both</span></span>, within a single <b><span class=\"wysiwyg-color-purple\">Hash Table</span></b>. We could, of course, store the student names and grades in separate <b><span class=\"wysiwyg-color-purple\">Hash Tables</span></b>, but how would we know which student has which grade?</span></span><br><img alt=\"\" height=\"294\" title=\"Image: https://ucarecdn.com/23f88623-1ffd-46d2-9e28-97739e0a9804/\" width=\"449\" src=\"https://ucarecdn.com/23f88623-1ffd-46d2-9e28-97739e0a9804/\"><br></p><p><span class=\"wysiwyg-color-green\"><span class=\"wysiwyg-color-black\"> Consequently, we want to find a way to be able to store a student name <i>with</i> his or her letter grade. This is where a </span></span><span class=\"wysiwyg-color-black\"><b><span class=\"wysiwyg-color-green\">Map</span></b></span><span class=\"wysiwyg-color-green\"><span class=\"wysiwyg-color-black\"> <b>Abstract Data Structure</b> comes into play! A <span class=\"wysiwyg-color-black\"><b><span class=\"wysiwyg-color-green\">Map</span></b></span> <b>ADT </b>allows us to store tuples in the format of &lt;<b><span class=\"wysiwyg-color-blue\">key</span></b>, value&gt; as opposed to just a single <b><span class=\"wysiwyg-color-blue\">key</span></b>.<br></span></span></p><p><br><img alt=\"\" height=\"150\" title=\"Image: https://ucarecdn.com/e9108a34-1aad-4123-b52d-be6e9d695028/\" width=\"523\" src=\"https://ucarecdn.com/e9108a34-1aad-4123-b52d-be6e9d695028/\"><br></p><p><span class=\"wysiwyg-color-green\"><span class=\"wysiwyg-color-black\">If we want to quickly check what grade Kammy has, we could hash into our Grade Book like so:</span></span></p><p></p><pre><code>cout &lt;&lt; Grade_Book['Kammy'] &lt;&lt; endl;\n\n// Output:\n// A\n</code></pre><br><p></p><p><span class=\"wysiwyg-color-green\"><span class=\"wysiwyg-color-black\">A</span></span> <span class=\"wysiwyg-color-black\"><b><span class=\"wysiwyg-color-green\">Map</span></b></span> <b>ADT</b><span class=\"wysiwyg-color-green\"><span class=\"wysiwyg-color-black\"> is often called an <i>associative array</i> because it gives us the benefit of being able to <i>associatively </i>cluster our data. However, unlike just a multidimensional array where we are also able to cluster our data, a</span></span><span class=\"wysiwyg-color-black\"><b><span class=\"wysiwyg-color-green\"> <span class=\"wysiwyg-color-black\"><b><span class=\"wysiwyg-color-green\">Map</span></b></span> <b></b></span></b></span><b><span class=\"wysiwyg-color-green\"><b><span class=\"wysiwyg-color-black\">ADT</span></b> </span></b><span class=\"wysiwyg-color-black\"><b> </b></span><span class=\"wysiwyg-color-green\"><span class=\"wysiwyg-color-black\">takes advantage of the </span></span><span class=\"wysiwyg-color-black\"><b><span class=\"wysiwyg-color-green\">hash function</span></b></span><span class=\"wysiwyg-color-green\"><span class=\"wysiwyg-color-black\"><b></b> to allow us to insert keys and values of <i>any</i> type in our backing array and be able to retrieve them fairly quickly. </span></span><br></p><br>", "options": {}, "subtitle_files": [], "name": "text", "video": null, "feedback_wrong": ""}, "id": "121797"}